{# A review the owner already replied to has been materially edited.

   The one thing this email has to convey: your published reply may no longer
   match what it's sitting under. Everything else is secondary.

   Required context: preheader, place_name, rating, stars, previous_rating,
   rating_changed, excerpt, inbox_url
#}{% extends "_base.html.jinja" %}

{% block content %}
<h1 style="margin: 0 0 16px 0; font-size: 22px; line-height: 1.3; font-weight: 700; color: #1a1a1a;">
  A review you replied to was updated
</h1>

<p style="margin: 0 0 16px 0; color: #555;">
  Someone changed their review of {{ place_name }} after you responded to it.
  Your reply is still public underneath it.
</p>

{% if rating_changed %}
<p style="margin: 0 0 8px 0; font-size: 18px; color: #b45309;">
  <span style="color: #9a9a9a; text-decoration: line-through;">{{ previous_rating }}/5</span>
  &nbsp;→&nbsp; {{ stars }} ({{ rating }}/5)
</p>
{% else %}
<p style="margin: 0 0 8px 0; font-size: 18px; color: #b45309;">{{ stars }} ({{ rating }}/5)</p>
{% endif %}

<p style="margin: 0 0 20px 0; padding: 12px 16px; background-color: #f6f7f6; border-radius: 8px; color: #333;">
  {{ excerpt }}
</p>

<p style="margin: 0 0 16px 0; color: #555;">
  Worth a look: if your reply thanked them for something they no longer say,
  it now reads as a response to words that aren't there. Editing your reply
  clears the "edited after this reply" note diners currently see.
</p>

<p style="margin: 0 0 16px 0; color: #555;">
  If your reply still stands, you don't need to do anything.
</p>

<p style="margin: 24px 0;">
  <a class="th-button" href="{{ inbox_url }}"
     style="display: inline-block; background-color: #6f8b3e; color: #ffffff; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; padding: 12px 22px; border-radius: 8px;">
    Review your reply
  </a>
</p>
{% endblock %}
